WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.000
Hi everybody, this talk will be on Shiny Data-centric web applications in Python

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:13.000
and this talk will be introducing Shiny for Python

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:16.000
and it's by Joe Cheng

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:18.000
A little bit of info about Joe

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:23.000
Joe is the CTO and first employee at Post-It PPC

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:25.000
formerly known as RStudio

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:31.000
where he helped create the RStudio IDE and Shiny web framework

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:34.000
along with countless complementary tools and packages

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:37.000
Please welcome Joe for his talk

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:44.000
Thanks Vincent

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Today I'm going to talk to you about Shiny for Python

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:52.000
a package for creating data-centric web applications in Python

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:57.000
This is an example of a pretty simple, typical Shiny app

00:00:57.000 --> 00:00:59.000
I'm going to go ahead and click it

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:04.000
and hopefully show you the live version

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:10.000
On the left we have some parameters that I can use to affect the graph

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:13.000
On the right, this is using Seaborn

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:18.000
and on the back end it's AppCandice or Polars or something, I don't remember

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:23.000
and on the top here I can show some big numbers

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:28.000
and my colleague who created this example app wanted to make sure that I clicked on the penguins

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.000
so you can see the lovely art by Alison Forst

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:44.000
So, Shiny is, as I said, it's for creating interactive apps and dashboards in Python

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:47.000
and we'll get into some of the different applications today

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:50.000
But I want to emphasize, because...

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:53.000
How many here have heard of Shiny before?

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:58.000
And how many of you have heard of Shiny in the context of R, not Python?

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:01.000
I want to make sure that it's clear because I've gotten this question

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:05.000
Shiny for Python is not a wrapper around Shiny for R

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:09.000
This is not like you have to install R to use Shiny for Python

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:16.000
Shiny for Python is a ground-up reimplementation of Shiny in PurePython

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:22.000
and it was designed primarily with data scientists in mind

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:24.000
and that has a couple of implications

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:28.000
Number one, we don't expect you to have web development skills

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.000
You can do tons and tons of stuff in PurePython

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.000
and it's based on this reactive programming approach to interactivity

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
that we specifically chose because it's easy to get started with

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:43.000
and relatively hard to make mistakes

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:51.000
On the other hand, I personally have been creating websites and web applications since 1996

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:55.000
It would be really frustrating for me personally if day in and day out

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:01.000
I was working on this web framework that felt lowest on the denominator in any way

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:03.000
or that it had artificial guardrails

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:06.000
So if you do have web development skills

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:10.000
you can fully leverage them to customize or extend your Shiny apps

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:12.000
and it seems like even in data science

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:15.000
more and more people seem to be picking up some of these skills

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:21.000
And the same reactive programming paradigm that is so easy to get started with

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:26.000
it's also powerful and flexible and deep as I hope to show you today

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.000
Just to get concrete here

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:35.000
this is what a Shiny app looks like in Shiny for Python

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:38.000
This is probably the simplest app

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:41.000
This is like a Hello World app basically

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.000
Every Shiny app has two main components

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:47.000
There's first the user interface

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:52.000
and this is Python code that generates HTML to send to the browser

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:55.000
And in this case, it's going to look something like this

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:57.000
So we have...

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:08.000
So in this case, we have an input slider and an output plot

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:13.000
And this app UI variable that it's creating is literally just HTML

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:17.000
Like if you were to print that out of Python, that's what you would see

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:22.000
And the other component is this server logic

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:25.000
that runs on the server at runtime

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:28.000
and it provides the interactivity of the app

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:33.000
In this case, if the user touches the slider and moves it to a new value

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:36.000
this input.n is automatically updated

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:39.000
and this entire function will run to generate a new plot

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:44.000
that is sent to whatever spot is designated in the UI

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:46.000
by output underscore plot there

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:52.000
So that's the basics of how a Shiny app is built

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
At the bottom is just a single line to create an app object

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:58.000
and assign it to an app variable

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:05.000
And this is what your user experience will be like as a developer

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:10.000
Using VS Code here, we have a Shiny for Python VS Code extension

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:14.000
So you can just click this play button here

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:16.000
if you have a Shiny app on the screen

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:19.000
And it will run the Shiny app at the bottom

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.000
putting you in the right virtual environment and things like that

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.000
And at the right, the application will appear

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:29.000
And as you save changes to your application Python code

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:32.000
it will go ahead and reload automatically

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:35.000
As you would expect in 2023 for a web framework

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:42.000
So let me show you a slightly more complicated example

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:45.000
than just that hello world

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:50.000
In this example, we are using the Astropy astronomy package for Python

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:55.000
to create a tool that helps astronomers know

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:57.000
when are the best times to look for

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:00.000
these specific celestial objects that they're interested in observing

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:03.000
This will show you when they'll be brightest in the night sky

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:06.000
depending on what day and what location on Earth you're in

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:09.000
And I'm going to show some code here

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:13.000
Don't worry if you don't try to ingest it all

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:16.000
I just want to point out a couple things about this kind of code

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:20.000
So in this Shiny UI, we're using some additional features

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:24.000
First of all, this is an h3 tag

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.000
In HTML that means heading level 3

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:30.000
So if you know HTML and you're familiar with HTML tags

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:33.000
you can directly access them by using these Python functions

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:36.000
that wrap the equivalent HTML tag

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:38.000
You can use markdown

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:42.000
In this case, we have a link in the middle that's using markdown syntax

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:47.000
And we can have rows and columns that have varying widths

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.000
We have outputs

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:53.000
We have inputs

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:58.000
And if you put all that together, you have a UI that looks like this

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.000
And one other thing that I want to point out

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:04.000
When I zoom out, there's sort of a shape to the code

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:09.000
Because it's nested functions, there's sort of a shape that the indentation gives it

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:11.000
And there's two big chunks here

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:13.000
One for the header and one for the body

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:19.000
And I really love this property that the shape of the code is reflected in the shape of the UI

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:23.000
And this is true in sort of a hierarchical way

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:26.000
So inside of that body, there are two columns

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:30.000
And you can see the shape of those columns reflected in the shape of the code

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.000
And as your apps get larger and more complicated

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:34.000
This is a really beautiful property

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:40.000
Because it means it's easy to find your way to the specific spot in your complex UI

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:43.000
Where you need to make changes

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:52.000
Okay, so we announced Shiny for Python about a little less than a year ago

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:55.000
And the news made the rounds

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:59.000
And on our data science subreddit

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:03.000
I think we had a pretty typical range of reactions

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:05.000
Some people were really excited

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:13.000
But other people were like this

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:18.000
But it's just so easy to throw something up with Streamlit

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:21.000
How many people here have heard of Streamlit?

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:24.000
Okay, how many people have used Streamlit?

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:27.000
Okay, so a few of you

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:33.000
And Streamlit has this reputation for being just so easy

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:36.000
And I want to examine that, unpack that a little bit

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:38.000
So imagine that you have a script.py

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:43.000
A totally normal linear Python script that is doing some data analysis

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:45.000
Let's say you're loading some data

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:48.000
You are maybe cleaning it a little bit

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:52.000
And then you're previewing a pandas data frame and then plotting it

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:58.000
The promise of Streamlit is that you can take pretty much that exact script

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:02.000
Sprinkle in some Streamlit to add some UI

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:07.000
And boom, you have now an interactive data product or what have you

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:11.000
And contrast that to Shiny

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:15.000
Which, if you've never seen Shiny before, even what I just showed you

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:20.000
Clearly, Shiny wants you to put code in the places where it tells you to

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:23.000
So it is a different approach

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:30.000
And this approach that they have of being able to write Streamlit apps

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:33.000
In the same way you write Python scripts

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:36.000
There's a very specific way they make this possible

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:41.000
Streamlit's architecture allows you to write apps the same way you write plain Python scripts

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:44.000
To unlock this, Streamlit apps have a unique data flow

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:47.000
Anytime something must be updated on the screen

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:52.000
Streamlit reruns your entire Python script from top to bottom

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:57.000
And let me be clear, it is easy

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:02.000
I mean, for simple Streamlit apps, it is unbelievably easy

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.000
You could learn Streamlit by accident

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:08.000
You could write a Streamlit app falling down the stairs

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:11.000
I mean, it is really, really easy

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:15.000
And they also have really nice-looking output

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:20.000
I mean, it's pretty hard to make a bad-looking Streamlit app

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:25.000
But this model also has limitations that are quite obvious

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:28.000
And especially with the early versions of Streamlit

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
You had this pretty slow performance

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.000
Because it's always executing the entire thing again and again

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:38.000
And pretty soon you need to start being pretty deliberate about caching values

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:42.000
And you have pretty limited opportunities for interactivity

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:46.000
Other than changing parameters, the whole thing kind of rebuilds

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:54.000
So Streamlit added some capabilities called caching, callbacks, and session state

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:58.000
And as people develop in their Streamlit journey

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:01.000
They find themselves relying more and more on these techniques

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:07.000
And this is where I sort of, I'm out, you know

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:12.000
The combination of this beautifully elegant top-to-bottom execution model

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.000
Plus these other features, I think this combination is actually quite dangerous

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:20.000
And I'm not going to elaborate too much more on this

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:22.000
This is not a talk about Streamlit

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:28.000
But I just want to make it clear that this is not something that I made up

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:35.000
I came to this conclusion by looking at the feedback that Streamlit's most rabid fans were giving them

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:39.000
So in the big picture context, I see one critical issue for Streamlit

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:44.000
The top-to-bottom rerun on every interaction paradigm

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:47.000
Maintaining state becomes really difficult

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:51.000
And there are just multiple examples where people found this model

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:58.000
At first super simple, and then ultimately kind of painted them into a corner

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:02.000
So what we've tried to do with Shiny and this reactive approach

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:08.000
Is to have a paradigm that's both easy to get started with and it scales

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:11.000
It scales as the complexity of your apps scale

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:17.000
It scales as the kinds of things you want to do to extend your apps increase

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:24.000
And over the last 10 years, as Shiny for R has proliferated on these same ideas of reactivity

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:29.000
We've seen people build rather complex data apps indeed

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:36.000
And a lot of the time, if you talk to our users and customers

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:39.000
Who are getting the most value out of Shiny

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:44.000
They're often building rather complex, not just a simple dashboard

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:47.000
Not just a simple model demonstrator

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:51.000
But really using Shiny for those things, yes

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:55.000
But also integrating into critical workflows

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:03.000
And this idea of reactivity that was really the kernel that started Shiny

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:07.000
Over the last 10 years, it's been unbelievable to me

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:10.000
How fertile this ground is for new ideas

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:15.000
That these small reactive primitives that we've been working with since 2012

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.000
Really can be combined in all these interesting ways

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:22.000
And features like this just sort of fall out left and right

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:27.000
And even after 10 years, last week getting ready for this talk

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:30.000
My colleague Winston Chang and I discovered a new way to use reactivity

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:34.000
To interact with async Python generators

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:39.000
In a way that made, you'll see, one of our demo applications possible

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:46.000
So now I'd like to launch into some demos

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:49.000
And it's 2020 for me, what is Tech Talk

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:53.000
Without some kind of large language model demo, right?

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:59.000
So this is a package that Winston has been working on

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:05.000
That basically makes it easier for him to scratch his own itch

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:09.000
Of playing with OpenAI's chat2BT API

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:15.000
So this is a super simple Shiny app that you can see here

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:19.000
We're importing this cat module, that's new

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:23.000
And with one line of UI and one line of server

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:31.000
And this is where I hope the API works well today

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:37.000
No, stop it

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:42.000
So, okay

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:45.000
With one line of UI and one line of server

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:48.000
I have a chat2BT interface

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:52.000
So I have like, why is the sky blue?

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:57.000
And the fact that this text is streaming in

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:00.000
This is that thing that we were playing with with async generators

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:05.000
You know, it's chat2BT, so why is the sky blue as a wrap?

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:12.000
So really easy, but

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:18.000
It's not that interesting if we're just inserting an island of chat2BT

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.000
Into a Shiny app, right?

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:23.000
What we really want to do is be able to interact with

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:28.000
And mess with the conversation between chat2BT and the user

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:31.000
So

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:35.000
For this next example

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:45.000
So, Winston again

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:48.000
Taking on Winston, I guess, this demo session

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:53.000
Winston recently bought a Samsung induction range

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:55.000
He really wanted me to tell you guys

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:58.000
He bought a fancy new Shiny induction range

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:01.000
And this range is pretty new

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:06.000
And chat2BT 3.5 is only current up to September 2021

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:08.000
Something like that

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:11.000
So, despite having a PhD

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:14.000
He was not able to figure out how to set the time

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:17.000
On the clock of his new stove

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:21.000
So

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:24.000
What this application lets you do is

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:28.000
Take a PDF, so in this case the Samsung induction range

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:35.000
User manual

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:38.000
And you upload it to this document

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.000
And now it's indexing, it's generating embeddings

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:46.000
And when I ask a question, it's going to send a context to chat2BT

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:56.000
So I can say, how do I set the time on the clock?

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:03.000
And it gives me a list of steps

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:11.000
Okay, great, and now our clock can stop flashing at 12

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.000
So, in this example

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:21.000
We had to change the payload that's being sent to chat2BT

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:24.000
Without having that interfere with the user experience

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:30.000
So that's one thing that this package lets you do

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:38.000
And then one more chat2BT example, and then I'll move on

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:42.000
So this one's a little different in that there are two chat2BTs

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:46.000
That I've embedded in this one app

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:51.000
And it's really fun to, you know, sort of compare

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:54.000
As you have one conversation, you can talk to another model

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:57.000
And ask it different things

00:17:57.000 --> 00:18:01.000
But let's play 20 questions

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:06.000
I'll ask, or I'll guess

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:09.000
Okay

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:14.000
And this app has this mode where you can have these two models talk to each other

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:17.000
So let's play 20 questions

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:20.000
You guess first

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:23.000
Go ahead and guess

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:26.000
And I can click this converse with self

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:30.000
And every time a response comes back from one of these conversations

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:33.000
It'll be directed to the other side

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:38.000
So now we are watching chat2BT play 20 questions with itself

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.000
Is it an object? Yes, it's an object

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:42.000
Is it commonly found? Yes

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:46.000
There's a lot of yeses, this is a little bit suspicious

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:49.000
I should have turned the temperature up, I guess

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:52.000
Can it be used for cooking food? Yes

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:55.000
Can it be used for cooking food? Is it made out of metal?

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:58.000
This is some BS, what is with all...

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:04.000
Honestly, this doesn't usually happen, this seems very rigged

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:07.000
Is it a frying pan?

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:09.000
Oh, it is a frying pan, so...

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.000
Come on

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:13.000
Okay

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:43.000


00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:50.000
Yeah, you never know, you never know what's going to come out

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:53.000
Yesterday when I tried this, it was just smiley emoji

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:56.000
And that was, it was that recursively

00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:00.000
Alright, that probably cost me like $2

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:04.000
Okay

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:09.000
So this package is available, this QR code

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:12.000
It's super, super wet cement

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:17.000
I mean, like, I think this has existed for like a total of four Christmas days now

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:21.000
So definitely, you know, API can change and things like that

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:25.000
But super fun to play around with

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:29.000
Okay

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:36.000
So for my next demo

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:42.000
This is using a demo that, an example that came from Plotly

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:46.000
So this is a Plotly widget on the right here

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:50.000
Showing a 3D visualization of Brownian motion

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:54.000
Now Brownian motion is like the random motion of a particle on a surface

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:58.000
Or in a volume of air or something like that

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:04.000
And I can hit new data here to generate new samples, new random samples

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:09.000
And some of these look really cool, and some of them

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:11.000
Like this one, it's a little harder to see what's going on

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:15.000
Just because of the random angle that the camera happens to be at

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:19.000
Now because this is Plotly, they have this feature where you can click and drag

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:22.000
And that's cool, right

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:27.000
But just for fun, for this example, we're going to do something different

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:37.000
So I'm using the Google Media Pipe library to track the position of my hand

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:43.000
So Google's doing all the heavy lifting, like detecting the length of marks on my hand

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:46.000
But Shiny is calculating a normal vector shooting out of my palm

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:51.000
And then using that to determine where the camera angle goes

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:55.000
And the reason I show you this, besides, you know, just that's kind of fun

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:58.000
Is this feature here, this smooth tracking

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:03.000
So if I turn this off, this is what this demo originally looked like

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:08.000
And, you know, when I got this working, I was like, oh my gosh, this is amazing

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:13.000
And my son is a senior in high school and is going to be a computer science major next year

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:15.000
I was like, come over and come look at this

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:20.000
And he was like, why is it so jittery?

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:24.000
I'm ungrateful

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:27.000
So, yeah, but, you know, it's a good question

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:31.000
Like, why is it so jittery? And it's jittery because sensors are jittery, right

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:33.000
But I thought it was an interesting question

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:35.000
Can we make it not so jittery?

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:36.000
So we tried a couple of things

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:41.000
We tried only registering movement if it was over a certain number of pixels

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:43.000
And that was like a complete mess

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:45.000
It was super stuttering and slow

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:52.000
And then we thought, like, what if we just average over the last five samples that we collect

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:54.000
And that's the approach here

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:57.000
It's just a simple mean over the last five samples

00:22:57.000 --> 00:23:00.000
And it works great, super smooth

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:08.000
And what's interesting about this

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:12.000
What's interesting about this is

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:16.000
It took about 10 minutes to implement that smoothing in 30-something lines of code

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:20.000
But what this is, is actually not a smoother for this app

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:26.000
This is a generalized smoother for any reactive value or source in Shiny

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:31.000
So that means that any kind of input that you have in Shiny that's fast and noisy

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:35.000
You can apply this function, tell it how many samples you want to smooth over

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:40.000
And provide your own algorithm for how you take n samples and collapse them into one

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:44.000
In my case, I was doing a mean, but you can do whatever you want

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:52.000
With this short snippet of code, we have generalized smoothing available in any Shiny app you can use

00:23:52.000 --> 00:23:55.000
And that's kind of what I was talking about

00:23:55.000 --> 00:24:05.000
We keep discovering these new applications of this technology called reactive programming

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:08.000
Just a couple more features I want to talk about

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:10.000
One is Shiny Live

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:15.000
Shiny Live is the combination of Shiny and the power of WebAssembly

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:19.000
Via the pretty famous at this point PyDive project

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:27.000
So if you haven't heard of it, PyDive is Python running inside of your web browser using WebAssembly

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:33.000
And what this lets you do is have an experience like this

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:36.000
Where we have this web page loaded

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:42.000
And there's actually nothing behind this web page other than HTML, CSS, and JavaScript

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:45.000
There is no server running Python

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:48.000
Python is running entirely within the browser

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:54.000
And this is just showing a real-time CPU graph

00:24:54.000 --> 00:25:00.000
Well, to be fair, one thing you cannot do in the browser is monitor the host computer's CPUs

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:02.000
So this is fake data

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:07.000
But if you imagine some other streaming data source, the same kind of techniques would apply

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:12.000
We have a Canvas-style data table at the bottom

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:21.000
And we can change this color palette to have different color maps

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:24.000
And this one is not awesome

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:28.000
So let's go ahead and remove that as an option

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:32.000
So we can come here and delete this

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:38.000
And if I press play, now it is reloaded and my update has taken effect

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:42.000
So pretty nice to be able to just come to this web page

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:45.000
You don't have to install Shiny on your mobile or anything

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:50.000
You can just start playing with Shiny through the shinylive.io website

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:55.000
And if you like what you've done here, you can even share it through a URL

00:25:55.000 --> 00:26:03.000
So if you want to send this to a friend that you want to see the code, then you can use this link

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:08.000
And they have basically the same editing experience as you did

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:14.000
Or you can click here and say, no, I want this just to feel like a full-on application

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:24.000
And it hides all the Chrome and just shows the app

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:32.000
So the nice thing about this is that the computation now is all happening on the browser

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:38.000
So you can actually use this technology to deploy Shiny apps to any static web host

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:44.000
You can put it on GitHub Pages or what have you instead of having to pay for Heroku

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:51.000
We also have free hosting, but if you wanted to put it on any static web host, you could

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:56.000
And you can also easily embed these kinds of Shiny applications in Quarto

00:26:56.000 --> 00:27:04.000
If you haven't heard of Quarto, it is a way of stitching together narrative through markdown

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:09.000
And computations and outputs of computations all together in beautiful documents

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:14.000
My colleague JJ O'Leary will be talking about that later this afternoon

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:19.000
And what this lets you do is it lets you combine these applications

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:28.000
Either bare like this or with a full editing experience directly into your documents and reports

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:30.000
Super easy to do

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:36.000
And we like that feature so much that we actually use Quarto to build our documentation website

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:41.000
So when you're learning Shiny, all of our examples take place in these little editors

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:49.000
And all of this is using Quarto and Shiny Live

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:53.000
One more feature, this is not available yet

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:59.000
This is something that we're working on, but I was really excited about it, so I wanted to at least give you a preview

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:08.000
We have a Shiny UI editor that's being developed that is a way to drag and drop your way to creating Shiny UI

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:13.000
So instead of writing the UI code that I showed you with nested function calls

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:18.000
You can use controls on the left, drag them onto this surface in the middle

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:22.000
And then use the pane on the right to modify properties

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:26.000
And all this is doing is just writing the same code you would write

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:32.000
So the end result is not a lot different than if you were to write it by hand

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:35.000
So you can change some properties on the slider here

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:38.000
So what you're seeing in the middle is just sort of a wireframe version of the application

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:44.000
It's not high fidelity, but in the lower right it's rendering a preview that is showing the live application

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:48.000
And you can click it to see what your application actually looks like

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:53.000
So still early days for this thing, but we expect to be rolling it out in the coming months

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:57.000
And we're super excited about making it easier for people to create

00:28:57.000 --> 00:29:02.000
Especially if you're building dashboards that have a bunch of rectangles on it

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:06.000
To get the spacing exactly right and to get the right proportions

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:11.000
It's one of those things that's easier when you're dragging and looking at it in real time

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:17.000
Than writing the code

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:20.000
Okay, that is it for me

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:24.000
If you are interested in writing powerful reactive web applications

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:28.000
I highly encourage you to go to shiny.plus.co.uk

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:33.000
We have examples and lots of articles and reference documentations there

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:36.000
That QR code is to the main website

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:42.000
And if you are interested in the source code of my examples minus the chat ones

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:45.000
They're at PyDataSeattle2023

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:51.000
And maybe in the middle of questions I'll switch over to show the other slide again

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:53.000
So yeah, thank you

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:03.000
So I tend to leave plenty of time for questions

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:06.000
Does anyone have any questions? Yes, in the back

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:12.000
Hi, I've never used Shiny, but I was just wondering if you could characterize

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:18.000
If I have some data on the back end that I want to reference or plug into this

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:23.000
Suppose I have a file that has a couple hundred thousand rows of data

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:28.000
What should I think about, or do you have a capacity?

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:30.000
Yeah, sure

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:36.000
I think the question was if you have data on the back end that's maybe a couple hundred thousand rows

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:40.000
Or really, I think the question you're asking is how do you get your data into this thing

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:43.000
And what size limitations do you need to worry about

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:50.000
So you can use any sort of Python code you want to load your data

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:57.000
And our example apps use Canvas and Polars and DuckTV

00:30:57.000 --> 00:31:02.000
And pretty much it's up to you how you want to load your data

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:09.000
Now there are a couple things that are worth talking about as far as scalability and things like that go

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:14.000
Number one, as a general rule, your data stays on the server

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:20.000
So if you're looking at a bunch of plots you made in Seaborn and that's it

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:26.000
Then you could load gigs of data and none of it is transferred over the wire

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:30.000
Just the actual outputs that the user is viewing

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:36.000
And that may sound obvious, but that's not true for all Python data science frameworks

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:43.000
Now I think the main thing that you'll have to worry about is, number one, is memory consumption

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:51.000
So in order to get good performance, you want to not be going back to reading a huge CSV

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:55.000
Every time the user kind of touches anything

00:31:55.000 --> 00:32:00.000
So by default, Shiny has these reactivity features

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:03.000
Actually on the screen here it says React and Calc

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:10.000
This is sort of a way to do very smart caching of your data as it changes

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:16.000
So in general, it'll cache the last copy, like the current copy of your data that you're displaying

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:24.000
So if you're loading a gigantic data frame and that is the result of your React and Calc expression

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:27.000
Shiny is going to hold one copy of that in memory

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:33.000
If you do a bunch of aggregation on it before you return it, then Shiny will just hold the aggregated values

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:37.000
Which could be much, much smaller

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:42.000
And also, I think as your data gets bigger, just like anything in Python data analysis

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:45.000
You start to look at sort of out-of-memory things

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:51.000
You start to look at things like .db or using a full-blown database or an OLAP system or something like that

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:55.000
And maybe not just loading CSVs into memory

00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:56.000
Yeah?

00:32:56.000 --> 00:32:59.000
I'm curious, how easy was it to move Shiny over to Python?

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:06.000
Like, Python has been used for web development for a long time compared to R

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:09.000
I'm just kind of curious if you have any feelings on that

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:13.000
Yeah, how hard was it to move Shiny over to Python?

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:16.000
I think it was one of those things that seemed really scary until we started

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:19.000
And then it went very quickly

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:25.000
And that includes having to really learn, like, Python's type annotation system

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:28.000
Wasn't something that existed the last time I really did any real Python

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:32.000
And that was something our whole team had to pick up and get good at

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:38.000
But, you know, I'd say like 90% of it was surprisingly fast

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:42.000
And then every once in a while there was something that, like

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:46.000
Creating the reference documentation took an ungodly amount of time

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:51.000
So there were, like, surprising things that ended up taking the other 90% of the time

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:52.000
Yeah?

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:58.000
What would be the difference between using something like Shiny and moving it to Qualys-Dash?

00:33:58.000 --> 00:34:02.000
Because we're designing it off what it's going to choose to be

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:05.000
So, you know, what were your expectations?

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:07.000
Yeah, I was expecting that

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:09.000
It took three minutes to get to that question

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:11.000
No, no, no, it's a really good question

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:14.000
And I almost addressed it in my talk

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:17.000
And then I just thought I'd leave it for a question

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:25.000
Well, every web framework has its own opinions about what's important

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:27.000
And we all make different payoffs

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:33.000
And in the particular case of Dash

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:39.000
The most opinionated thing they did was they made the server stateless

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:45.000
And that means that there is no memory in Dash

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:48.000
Between one invocation of a callback and another

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:52.000
So it's kind of like, to me, that has always puzzled me

00:34:52.000 --> 00:34:54.000
As the choice that they made

00:34:54.000 --> 00:35:04.000
Because it introduces such annoying limitations for the app author

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:07.000
And really mostly has a marginal benefit

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:10.000
For the people who ultimately have to deploy the app

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:12.000
I actually was curious about this

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:15.000
I was going to make this assertion that it has this big downside

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:18.000
And fairly marginal upside

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:22.000
And I think we have a lot of customers that use Shiny for R

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:24.000
And Dash for Python

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:27.000
And I don't think anyone has ever said

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:30.000
Oh, and we love that Dash is serverless

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:32.000
I mean, stateless

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:39.000
It doesn't matter for the vast majority of especially data-oriented applications

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:43.000
But listen, I'm here to learn

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:46.000
So if you are a Dash user and you love Dash

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:50.000
And I'm wrong and you love the stateless aspect of it

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:54.000
Then absolutely please come talk to me at the deposit booth

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:59.000
But I will say, I think when people start to realize

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:02.000
How much state is being transferred to the server

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:05.000
Every single time you touch anything

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:07.000
Like if you upload a CSV

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:10.000
You're really just holding it in the client

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:12.000
And every single output that renders

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:14.000
Every single time they render

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:16.000
You have to send that data to the server

00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:18.000
In every XHR call

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:21.000
And that's just a really surprising tradeoff to me

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:25.000
So in fairness, Dash Plotly has a page about

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:27.000
Like they know this is a problem

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:28.000
Like here are all these mitigations

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:33.000
But to me, that exact problem that they have workarounds for

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:34.000
Was the heart of Shiny

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:36.000
Like the heart of Shiny is that you have this state

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:38.000
That you're going to want to use again and again

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:42.000
As you tweak through the different possibilities of your analysis

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:44.000
And what we treated as core

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:48.000
They treated as sort of a little more of an afterthought

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:52.000
Maybe this is kind of piggybacking off of her question

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:56.000
But we use Bokeh a lot, like a Bokeh server

00:36:56.000 --> 00:36:59.000
And we have that in the Flask framework

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:02.000
Do you have this ability to change

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:04.000
To embed the server

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:07.000
Because we have this huge production of Bokeh in Flask

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:08.000
Sure, sure, sure

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:10.000
Yeah, so the question was

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:15.000
At your work, did they embed Bokeh

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:17.000
Or really integrate Bokeh applications

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:20.000
Into larger applications that are written in Flask

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:22.000
So almost

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:25.000
Shiny is not based on Flask

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:29.000
But based on the newer ASGI frameworks

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:32.000
So it is based on Starlet or FastAPI

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:33.000
You've heard of that

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:37.000
So you can combine Shiny with FastAPI applications

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:42.000
In exactly the same way that you can combine Bokeh with Flask

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:46.000
That being said, for existing Flask applications

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:49.000
The other way you could go, which people do with Shiny for R

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:52.000
Is to aggregate at the proxy layer

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:56.000
So you would run an Nginx server in front of both servers

00:37:56.000 --> 00:38:00.000
And then use that to basically map Shiny onto

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:03.000
Your Shiny app onto a certain URL path

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:06.000
I'm making it sound more complicated than it is

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:09.000
Yeah, yeah, okay

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:11.000
Yeah, over here in front

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:15.000
So if you are running a stateful server

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:21.000
How do you handle multiple people accessing Shiny at the same time?

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:23.000
Yeah, so the question was

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:25.000
If we're a stateful server

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:28.000
How do we handle multiple people accessing the server at the same time?

00:38:28.000 --> 00:38:30.000
And that is an excellent question

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:33.000
There are a couple ways that you do that

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:37.000
So let me first talk about multiple people hitting the same server

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:40.000
Or the same Python process

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:46.000
So this server function

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:50.000
Is actually invoked once per visitor

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:53.000
Or once per, we call that a session

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:55.000
But it's like a browser tab, basically

00:38:55.000 --> 00:39:00.000
So each visitor that arrives

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:05.000
Gets their own copy of this input-output in a session

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:08.000
So everything that you do inside of this server function

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:11.000
Is isolated to that one user

00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:15.000
But a really interesting consequence of this architecture

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:17.000
That I really love

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:21.000
Is that you can put things here

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:24.000
So you can put reactive objects here

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:26.000
And then they're actually shared by all users

00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:29.000
So you can decide what things are global

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:32.000
What things are specific to each user

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:35.000
Now the other question you might be wondering is

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:38.000
If you have multiple servers in a cluster

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:42.000
How do you, you know, there's something in memory

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:44.000
On a particular server

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:46.000
How do you make sure that it's routed?

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:50.000
So for that we just ask that you turn on sticky load balancing

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:53.000
Which every load balancer has that feature

00:39:53.000 --> 00:39:55.000
And pretty much pops off

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:57.000
Yeah, in the back there

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:00.000
I have some questions

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:02.000
So when you share Shiny apps

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:07.000
Is there any obfuscation from underlying data

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:09.000
That comes through?

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:12.000
So if you're sharing apps outside of your organization

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:14.000
Or a conference or anything like that

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:18.000
Is it easy to create some stack

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:20.000
And get all the underlying data

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:23.000
Or is there some security?

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:25.000
Oh man, can you imagine if I answered

00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:27.000
Like yes, it's easy to get at the underlying data

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:29.000
That would be real bad

00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:31.000
No, so for Shiny

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:34.000
It is, at the end of the day, it's a web application

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:37.000
So the messages that are going back and forth over the wire

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:39.000
Are the inputs and the outputs

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:42.000
The underlying data, the underlying code

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:45.000
Remains locked away on the server

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:48.000
The one exception to that is this Shiny live mode

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:50.000
Where everything's running on the client

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:53.000
Well in that case, everything's being shipped to the client

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:56.000
So if you have hard-coded a password

00:40:56.000 --> 00:40:58.000
Into your Shiny application

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:01.000
And then ship it via Shiny live to the browser

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:03.000
Well, yeah, you've made a mistake

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:06.000
But if you host it any of the traditional ways

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:08.000
Where Python is running on the server

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:11.000
And the front end is just showing pictures

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:13.000
And giving you inputs

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:15.000
Then everything is perfectly safe

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:17.000
The same way it would be in Flask

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:19.000
The same way it would be in Django

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:21.000
Or any other web application framework

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:24.000
So you're comparing it to Flask and Django, FastAPI

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:27.000
Is the CICE, like this looks like really

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:30.000
From a developer's perspective

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:32.000
Super easy to get up and running

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:35.000
And the logical next question is

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:38.000
Okay, now I need people at my organization to use this

00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:40.000
I need it to get deployed

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:42.000
I need it to get updates, improvements

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:44.000
Is that kind of standard?

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:46.000
Or are there any additional considerations

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:49.000
Beyond the typical FastAPI development and deployment?

00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:52.000
Yeah, yeah, you sound like someone who works for a living

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:56.000
That's a very practical and important question

00:41:56.000 --> 00:41:58.000
So the question was

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:00.000
Yeah, this seems great for whoever is writing the application

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:02.000
But when it comes to the time to deploy it

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:05.000
And integrate it into CICE pipelines

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:07.000
And keep it up and keep it stable

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:09.000
Is there anything that you need to be aware of?

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:11.000
So in terms of the deployment

00:42:11.000 --> 00:42:16.000
It feels pretty much like a typical FastAPI type app

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:19.000
However

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:24.000
I'd say if you write a traditional Django or FastAPI type app

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:26.000
The testing can be easier

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:29.000
Because really what you're writing

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:32.000
For most of those sort of lower-level web frameworks

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:34.000
Is a series of endpoints

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:36.000
And with Shiny, all this interactivity

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:38.000
This is happening over a WebSocket

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:41.000
There's no reason why that's not inherently testable

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:43.000
But most people in most organizations

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:45.000
Do not have a lot of experience

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:47.000
Testing WebSocket-based applications

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:49.000
So I will say we have been using Playwright

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:52.000
If you use Playwright or Cypress as testing frameworks

00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:54.000
They work awesome

00:42:54.000 --> 00:42:57.000
And Playwright will even let you inspect the WebSocket traffic

00:42:57.000 --> 00:42:59.000
As it goes through

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:02.000
But yes, if you have people that are used to testing Django apps

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:04.000
Specifically the testing aspect

00:43:04.000 --> 00:43:06.000
And also the load testing aspect

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:08.000
It's probably going to throw them for a loop for a little bit

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:10.000
But other than that

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:12.000
I mean, to be honest

00:43:12.000 --> 00:43:14.000
The turnaround times on building these kinds of apps

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:16.000
For people who know a little bit of Shiny

00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:18.000
It is so dramatically different

00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:20.000
Than what it is for using

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:22.000
And by the way, the same is true for Streamlit and Dash

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:25.000
You were talking about a different order of magnitude

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:27.000
Of velocity

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:29.000
Versus using sort of these lower-level frameworks

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:33.000
That, you know, people get

00:43:33.000 --> 00:43:35.000
That there are going to be these kinds of tradeoffs

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:37.000
Where the wires are not quite as visible

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:39.000
And you can't instrument them quite as well

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:42.000
Yeah

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:44.000
One final question

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:46.000
Or no, you guys are out

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:48.000
That's fine

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:50.000
Thank you very much

